element_texts.text: Oak Grove Farm  Tiskilwa Ill., Mar 27 1917  Dear Doctor Taylor:- I enclose herewith a draft for $50.00 payable to your order. It is from a fund left by Mrs. Cushing in her will for me to distribute, and you are to use it for any kind of work at "The Commons" where, in your judgment, it will do the most good. Life has been pretty lonely for me this winter and I am glad that spring is hear. With best wishes I am Fraternally yours E. Blenshing. Kindly sign and return the enclosed executor's receipt.

Chicago 7/24/1932
My Dear Dr. Taylor
As a member of The Sentinels of the Republic who for many years have been fighting Bureaucracy & [impaction] of state's rights by the Congress of the U.S. I take exception to your article in the news last-night.
I am enclosing clippings from to-day's Tribune which will substantiate me.
I might cite the vicious Shephard-Towner bill which they are trying to pass under another cloak & which was an unwarranted expenditure of public funds & a perfect failure according to [which] authorities

If Congress does not cut their expenses as Industrial corporations have the latter will not be able to do business & therefore unemployment will increase. About two months ago I heard family Judge Jarecki give an address at the Women's Club. He said that when the French peasants asked for bread & were told to eat grass it was no very long till the blood of the nobility was running in the streets.
When England goaded this country with taxes a revolution was the result. He said that a few reds could not collect in the back of a
